{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636758"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:33:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:33:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17602"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17602"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10316"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77689"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10316"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17602"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63202"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10016"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24125"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24130"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77689"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPancreatic juice consists of multiple digestive enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the composition of pancreatic juice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low bicarbonate and active enzymes","High bicarbonate and inactive enzymes","No bicarbonate and inactive enzymes","High bicarbonate and active enzymes","Low bicarbonate and inactive enzymes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPancreatic fluid contains \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh concentrations of bicarbonate and inactive digestive enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E. The bicarbonate concentration can reach 140 mmol/L, which neutralises acidic chyme entering from the stomach. Enzymes are secreted in inactive forms (zymogens) to prevent autodigestion of the pancreas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh bicarbonate and active enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - Active enzymes would damage pancreatic tissue\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow bicarbonate and inactive enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - Low bicarbonate would not effectively neutralise stomach acid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow bicarbonate and active enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - This combination would neither neutralise acid nor protect pancreatic tissue\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo bicarbonate and inactive enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - Bicarbonate is essential for neutralising stomach acid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe composition of pancreatic fluid is regulated by two main hormones: secretin stimulates bicarbonate secretion, while cholecystokinin stimulates enzyme secretion. The enzymes become activated only after entering the duodenum, where enterokinase converts trypsinogen to trypsin, which then activates other pancreatic enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pancreatic fluid contains high concentrations of bicarbonate (HCO3-) which neutralises acidic chyme entering the duodenum.","The pancreas secretes digestive enzymes in an inactive form to prevent autodigestion of pancreatic tissue.","Pancreatic secretions are stimulated by secretin (for bicarbonate) and cholecystokinin (for enzymes)."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. Available from: https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63202"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17602"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63202"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T21:57:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T21:58:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10316"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77689"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null